   "narrative": "Harold Louis Guyon of Holyoke served as a Fireman First Class aboard the heavy cruiser USS Indianapolis — a rating that lived deep below the waterline, in the boiler and engine rooms, where a man tended the fires and turbines that drove the ship and had the farthest of anyone to climb if she went down. The Indianapolis had just delivered the components of the atomic bomb to Tinian and was steaming unescorted toward Leyte when, shortly after midnight on July 30, 1945, the Japanese submarine I-58 put two torpedoes into her. She sank in twelve minutes. About three hundred men went down with the ship. Some nine hundred went into the water, and for four days and five nights, without rescue and without water, they were taken by exposure, thirst, and sharks. Only three hundred and sixteen came out alive. It was the worst disaster at sea in the history of the United States Navy, and Harold Guyon of Holyoke did not survive it. He was survived by his wife, Mrs. Flora Almanda Guyon. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
