   "narrative": "Edwin M. Mitchell of Holyoke entered the service on February 26, 1918, was stationed at Camp Devens, transferred to Camp Upton on Long Island, and arrived overseas in April 1918 with a machine gun unit. He was transferred to Company I, 308th Infantry — the regiment that would give the war its Lost Battalion. On August 22, 1918, following a German raid on the American front-line trenches, he was reported missing. Word came unofficially that he was a prisoner. His family held that hope for six months. In February 1919, three months after the Armistice, the War Department declared that he had been killed in action, date undetermined. Holyoke did not forget him: Prospect Field was renamed Edwin J. Mitchell Field in 1933 and dedicated in his honor in 1937, and it bears his name still — a soldier's name on ground where the city's children play. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
