   "narrative": "Arthur J. Perreault entered the service in June 1917 and was sent to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology for preliminary flight training. He received his commission in September 1917 and went to England that December, transferring to the Royal Flying School at Paris. He was the first Holyoke man to pilot an aeroplane in France for the United States Army — a distinction earned in the earliest days of American military aviation, when the aircraft were still called simply \"machines,\" were built of wood, wire, and doped fabric, and carried no parachute for the man flying them. Lieutenant Perreault was killed in an aeroplane accident in France on March 7, 1918, while serving with the 3rd Aero Squadron. A board of officers found his death to be in the line of duty. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
